title: For Sale:  Bersa Thunder 380
postcontent: I am getting rid of my Bersa Thunder 380.  It's an Argentinian Walther PPK clone, all metal, DA/SA with decocker/safety.  It also has a manual lock (key on left side of frame) and a magazine safety where the trigger won't operate without a magazine in the frame.  Some people don't like all these safety features, but I personally bought this gun for them as I have young children and don't mind the added hassle for peace of mind. I carry it loaded and chambered with the safety off and hammer down, so there's the long first DA pull but each after that is SA and smooth (like a Beretta).  It shoots 380, is super accurate, and super reliable.  No FTF, jams, or misfires with either FMJ or Hollowpoints.  I've shot 200 rounds through it and it functions great. I bought this for an all around self defense/carry/home defense gun, but am moving on.  Great little gun, small and comfortable to carry, can put a whole magazine in a couple of inches at 10 yards.Everything in the pictures comes for the selling price: the original case, manual, and lock; the pistol; one 7 round magazine; one 9 round magazine with extended grips (great if you have big hands), and an "Uncle Mike's" soft IWB holster (I've worn this all day in shorts, jeans, etc. No printing); and one 50 round box of Fiocchi FMJ ammo.Would be interested in a trade/partial trade for a revolver with a 4" or shorter barrel (snubs are ok), preferably in 357/38sp. Let me know what you have and see if we can work a deal.  Will have to meet at FFL for transfers/background checks. I know a cheap place or you can pick your favorite.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ballester Molina British Contract .45
postcontent: British World War II military pistol manufactured by Hispano-Argentina Fabricas de Automoviles SA in Buenos Aires, Argentina. This is one of the approximately 8000 pistols ordered by the British Purchasing Agency and issued to the SOE (Strategic Operations Executive) and other British clandestine organizations fighting the Nazis in occupied Europe. This is an all correct British contract pistol with the distinctive "B" prefixed serial number. Following the end of the war these pistols were released  to the commercial market and then were marked with the current British proof marks (post 1956) on the right side of slide and frame, "Crown over P". The barrel displays British pressure test proofs and the caliber designation. Left side of the slide is marked: "PISTOLA AUTOMATICA CAL.45 FABRICADA POR 'HAFDASA' PATENTES INTERNACIONALES 'BALLESTER-MOLINA' INDUSTRIA ARGENTINA" (in three lines, please note the correct "Cal45" caliber designation). 5" barrel. 7 shots magazine. Matching serial numbers, frame, slide and barrel. These pistols were manufactured with two sets of numbers: the maker number stamped on the left side of the pistol grip, just behind the wooden stock, and the British contract "B" serial number. All complete and in as issued military configuration. Please make a cash offer or trade.
